<!-- New Section 2, Sketch an overall picture of ICN architecture -->
<section title="A Sketch of the Big Picture of an ICN Network Architecture">
	<t>An ICN network fetches data by names.  This is accomplished by defining two types of packet format: interest packet that requests a piece of named content, and the data packet that carries the requested content.  Every data packet must be cryptographically signed which binds its name and content together.  A basic set of ICN concepts is listed below:
	</t>
	
	<t>Data Naming:</t>
	
	<t>ICN name granularity is per packet.  If a piece of application content's size exceeds the network packet size limit, the content is segmented and each data packet is uniquely named with content name concatenated with the segment number. 
	</t>
	
	<t>
	Each ICN data packet is immutable.  This is accomplished by assigning a version number to each piece of application content.  When the content changes, the version number in its name changes as well.
	</t>
	
	<t>Data-centric security: </t>
	
	<t>Each ICN data packet carries a signature that binds its name and content together, allowing a named packet to be fetched from anywhere and the user is still able to verify its validity.
	</t>
	
	<t>ICN node: A node in an ICN network may play anyone or a combination of the three roles: a data producer, a data consumer, and a forwarder for interest and data packets.  Note that a forwarder can be a packet mule, that is it may carry an interest or data packet over some distance before forwarding it to next node.
	</t>
	
	<t>Stateful forwarding plane: An ICN forwarder keeps three data structures: a FIB, a Pending Interest Table (PIT), and a Content Store (CS). When it receives an ICN interest packet, it checks CS and PIT to find an matching name; if no matching found, it records the interest in PIT and forwards it to the next hop(s) toward the requested content.
	</t>
	
</section>


